04055nam a22005895i 9780822393993DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20132013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223939937 a10.1515/97808223939932doi  a(DE-B1597)553891  a(OCoLC)1202623727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aNX584.A1bM37 2013eb 7aART0151102bisacsh04a709.52/090462231 aMarotti, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoney, Trains, and Guillotines :bArt and Revolution in 1960s Japan /cWilliam Marotti. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b125 illustrations, incl. 19 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology of Select Events -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Art against the Police -- tPart II. Artistic Practice Finds Its Object -- tPart III. Theorizing Art and Revolution -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the 1960s a group of young artists in Japan challenged official forms of politics and daily life through interventionist art practices. William Marotti situates this phenomenon in the historical and political contexts of Japan after the Second World War and the international activism of the 1960s. The Japanese government renewed its Cold War partnership with the United States in 1960, defeating protests against a new security treaty through parliamentary action and the use of riot police. Afterward, the government promoted a depoliticized everyday world of high growth and consumption, creating a sanitized national image to present in the Tokyo Olympics of 1964. Artists were first to challenge this new political mythology. Marotti examines their political art, and the state's aggressive response to it. He reveals the challenge mounted in projects such as Akasegawa Genpei's 1,000-yen prints, a group performance on the busy Yamanote train line, and a plan for a giant guillotine in the Imperial Plaza. Focusing on the annual Yomiuri Indépendant exhibition, he demonstrates how artists came together in a playful but powerful critical art, triggering judicial and police response. Money, Trains, and Guillotines expands our understanding of the role of art in the international 1960s, and of the dynamics of art and policing in Japan.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aArts and societyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtsxPolitical aspectszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aArts, Japanesey20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturezJapan. 7aART / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393993zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393993423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393993.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles